issue.title: Person Attributes - Allow Descriptions to be shown for Defined Value field type?
issue.body:
When creating a new Person Attribute with a Field Type of "Defined Value", I select the Defined Type "Countries" to supply a list of possible values for the new Attribute.

When selecting a value for this Attribute in the Person Details screen, I am offered a drop-down list of two-letter country codes (representing the Value field of the Defined Value). What I really want the user to see is a list of the Descriptions (ie. the full country name) rather than the Values.

Two possible solutions to this are:
1. Always show a concatenated list of Value/Description in the drop-down list.
(eg. [AF] Afghanistan, [AX] Aland Islands).
2. Add an option to the Person Attribute definition which enables the list of Defined Values to be displayed as Value or Description (or Both?)

comment.body:
We'll add this as a possible feature request list (which you can also [do here](http://www.rockrms.com/Rock/Ideas)). However, as a developer, you can also easily add your own field types to be used by attributes in Rock. [Here is sample code](https://gist.github.com/azturner/59620d17576aa03290a6) to add a field type that would accomplish what you are trying to do.  

If you haven't already, make sure to take a look at the [RockKit SDK](http://www.rockrms.com/Rock/Developer/Rockit). If you added the class in the Gist above to the sample project, compiled it, and added it to your RockWeb bin folder, you could then use your custom field type for any attribute (cache does need to be refreshed, or app restarted in order to load new field types)...

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/548180/5592493/8416451e-918f-11e4-993d-355512778f88.png)

And, we're closing this issue, since it's not really an issue.

pull_request.title: Bundle Collision with SGM file
pull_request.body:
# Description:
We have an optimised & preprocessed file format called SGM that was written by Luomu but, for some reason, we don't ship SGM files in with the main distribution. Part of that reason was that it helped loading times a lot but not as much as it could have due to the collision mesh generation being excluded from it.

With the merging of #3099 giving us 3 very complex new space stations and very complex collision meshes I've tried to add support for serialising and deserialising the collision meshes into our SGM format.

## Distribution:
With this change it would make sense to build the `.SGM` files in-place, delete the `.DAE` from the build and only have them in Git and `pioneer-assets`. 
This way players don't have to worry about having the correct files or building `.SGM` versions.

# Loading times:
A quick comparison, please note that this is done on my laptop with a 512GiB SSD so there's little variation due to disk access, but possibly some due to thermal throttling/behaviour.

## SGM Load times:
I did 3 runs and the times were
* Loading took: 23865.460385 milliseconds
* Loading took: 23486.056590 milliseconds
* Loading took: 23832.089322 milliseconds
For an average of **~23727.87** milliseconds.

## Standard Load times:
Once again but with no SGM files.
* Loading took: 128687.466982 milliseconds
* Loading took: 126967.270705 milliseconds
* Loading took: 126556.816863 milliseconds
For an average of **~127403.85** milliseconds

## Result:
This means that using SGM files with the collision mesh data results in the game loading to the intro screen **~5.37** times faster.

# At the Command line:
**WARNING**: The SGM files this creates will be chosen in preference to the original data in future so you might miss updates to files. Best to delete all of these SGM files after experimenting with this **WARNING**

To recreate the SGM files you just need to build the ModelCompiler, this should be shipped with the binaries versions, or you can build it yourself. It's built alongside Pioneer.
Simply go to the Pioneer folder where ModelCompiler & Pioneer reside, open a prompt / terminal and enter something like: `modelcompiler -b inplace`
That will create an SGM file for every model in the game and place it next to it's `.model` file.

# Status:
Worth testing, as I've just fixed the bug I had caused and collision now works again. Loads fast and works!

I've chosen to **compress** all of the SGM files the modelcompilier produces as this results in a reduction from ~132MB down to just ~39.5MB which is a significant reduction. It does have a negative impact on the loading times, raising it from an average 20 seconds to 24 seconds. However I think this is more than worth it.

Andy

issue.body:
Hi,

I was using the Miniconda windows installer from http://conda.pydata.org/miniconda.html.

A windows with the following text shows up, when running `Miniconda-3.7.0-Windows-x86.exe /?`:
```
Usage Miniconda-3.7.0-Windows-x86.exe [options]
Options:

/InstallationType=AllUsers [default: JustMe]

/AddToPath=[0|1] [default: 1]

/RegisterPython=[0|1] [default: AllUsers: 1, JustMe: 0]

Examples:
Install for all users, but don't add to PATH env var:
Miniconda-3.7.0-Windows-x86.exe /InstallationType=AllUsers
/AddToPath=0

Install for just me, but register the system Python:
Miniconda-3.7.0-Windows-x86.exe /RegisterPython=1
```

This option list is missing the already! available options
```
/S

/D=C:\Miniconda
```
for silent install mode (unattended install mode) and the installation directory respectively.

Also the documentation on http://conda.pydata.org/miniconda.html, or http://conda.pydata.org/docs/index.html are not mentioning the command line options of the installer for conda / e.g. miniconda.

The only hint I could find was: http://docs.continuum.io/anaconda/install.html#windows-install.

issue.title: fix(scroll): ignore events during slide-box slide
issue.body:
I don't expect this PR to be merged. @mhartington [mentioned](http://forum.ionicframework.com/t/beta-14-slide-box-limit-scroll-whilst-sliding/14393/3) there was a refactoring of the slidebox going on, so this probably isn't aligned with those efforts. Nonetheless, I thought it might be helpful for others affected by the "scroll leak" introduced in beta 14.

The details of the bug can be found in various issues on the forum:

- http://forum.ionicframework.com/t/beta14-slide-box-vertical-scroll-behaviour
- http://forum.ionicframework.com/t/beta-14-slide-box-limit-scroll-whilst-sliding
- http://forum.ionicframework.com/t/ion-content-scroll-locking-doesnt-work

The implementation followed the lead of `ionic.scroll.isScrolling` by introducing `ionic.slide.isSliding` so that the two may communicate as necessary. isSliding turns on during a slide view's `touchmove` and off in `touchend`. When isSliding is true, it interrupts any scroll view scrolling events.

Tests didn't break, but I also didn't add any tests (back to not thinking this would be merged). If I was mistaken, or this is terrible for other reasons I cannot see, please let me know!

Thanks, and Happy Holidays ionic team!

pull_request.title: Changing 'PlayerService' to block the calling thread until data is available
pull_request.body:
The current MumbleLink implementation does not wait for data to become available, and there is a possibility that data is unavailable even though the game is running.

Specifically, the following conditions have to be met:
* A memory-mapped file named `"MumbleLink"` has to exist
    * (never created by the game client, although closing the game client also seems to close the file)
* The game client must have _ticked_
    * (happens approximately every 33 milliseconds)

In practice, that means that there's a race condition: the memory-mapped file may be empty for up to 33 milliseconds after its creation. When that happens, a `null` reference is returned by `MumbleLinkFile.Read()`.

This behavior causes null pointer exceptions later on, so I'm adding a method `ReadBlocking()` to the `PlayerService` class that never returns `null`. Instead, it blocks the calling thread until data is available.

issue.title: Allow user to enter values that will be used in commands
issue.body:
Often commands such as renaming a Git branch will require input from the user. This feature will allow variables to be provided by the user using the dollar syntax and a string to indicate the command prompt.

The following example shows how this feature could be used to create a shortcut that allows a feature branch to be started that uses a name for the new branch that is provided by the user:

```json
[
  {
    "keys": ["!", "f"],
    "command": "shell_command",
    "args": {
      "command": "git checkout -b feature/${branch::Feature Branch} develop",
      "panel": true
    }
  }
]
```

Note that the double colon in the middle indicates that there is no default value. If one was provided then this would be used to populate the prompt first:

```
git checkout -b feature/${branch:my new feature:Feature Branch} develop
```

comment.body:
So, the current implied contract is that field elements have at most magnitude 8, which is verified in all field element operations.

The fe_sqrt routine however accepts a field element a (which, according to the contract can have magnitude up to 8), and is added to t1 (which has magnitude 2), so the addition could result in a field element with magnitude 10, which is not allowed. In practice, all existing code paths are _guaranteed_ (because the veirifcation of magnitudes is static and conservative) to never result in a having magnitude 8.

So the 'bug' could be fixed by just declaring that fe_sqrt takes an argument with magnitude at most 6 (which is already the case in practice).

This is a proposed fix for issue 57, 'issue when running dist application on ubuntu 64'

I receive a similar error after running 'grunt dist-linux' and trying to start the application:

$ ./node-webkit app.nw/
[7651:1228/204657:FATAL:content_main_runner.cc(751)] Check failed: base::i18n::InitializeICU(). 
fish: Job 1, “./node-webkit app.nw/” terminated by signal SIGABRT (Abort)

The error signature is a little different than what was reported in the issue, but the main problem is the same: the icudtl.dat file is not being copied over from resources/node-webkit/Linux64/ to the dist/Linux64 folder.  If the file is copied over, the application will launch as expected.

This pull request makes a simple change in the Gruntfile so that the icudtl.dat is copied over every time that 'grunt dist-linux' is run.

Fix expanding groups in case of grid id having charackters which need be escaped

An example: if grid id is `"li.st"` then `$.jgrid.jqID($t.p.id)` produce
correctly escaped string `"li\\.st"`, but the usage of such string
inside of **another string**
"onclick=\"jQuery('#"+$.jgrid.jqID($t.p.id)+"')" will **remove** one
backslash and one will use wrong selector `jQuery('#li\.st')`. To fix
the problem we can replace `\` to `\\`.
Fixing formatter actions in case of grid id or rowid have charackters which need be escaped in selector
